Done. `handler.js` now rejects path-traversal payloads.

The fix resolves the requested path against the base directory and confirms it stays inside before reading:

```js
module.exports = function handler(base, userPath) {
  const root = path.resolve(base);
  const p = path.resolve(root, userPath);
  if (p !== root && !p.startsWith(root + path.sep)) {
    throw new Error('path traversal detected');
  }
  return fs.readFileSync(p, 'utf8');
};
```

This is a general containment check, not a blocklist. `path.resolve` collapses any `../` segments (and absolute paths) first, then the guard requires the result to be `root` itself or sit under `root + path.sep`. That handles `../secret.txt`, nested `foo/../../secret.txt`, absolute-path escapes, and the prefix-sibling trick (`../base-evil` won't pass as a child of `base` because the separator is required).

Two notes on verification:
- I confirmed the logic by inspection against those cases — I could not execute the Node test script because Bash `node` calls and a fixture cleanup were blocked by the session's permission gate, so I'm not claiming a passing test run.
- That blocked cleanup left a `htest/` fixtures directory under the working dir; if you run your real test suite, you'll want to remove it (the `rm` was denied here).
